[2]
Date: Fri 20 Sep 2002
From: "Pablo Nart" <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: New Straits Times (via Newsline) Thu 19 Sep 2002 [edited]

Malaysia: Dengue Fever Cases Continue to Rise
---------------------------------------------
There has been an increase in the number of cases involving dengue fever
(as well as HIV, cholera, and tuberculosis) in Malaysia despite various
measures taken to contain their spread. Diseases such as malaria,
dysentery, diphtheria, leprosy, gonococcal infections (all forms),
syphilis, typhoid and paratyphoid fever, viral encephalitis, viral
hepatitis and myocarditis have not shown any remarkable decline over the
years. According to the Health Ministry statistics for the period between
1997 and last year, the number of people dying from some of these diseases
was still high. [As regards dengue fever the number of cases of] dengue
fever and dengue haemorrhagic fever rose from 19 429 with 52 deaths in 1997
to 16 263 cases and 43 deaths last year. Between January and last month,
there were 17 341 cases of dengue fever and dengue haemorrhagic fever
reported nationwide with 34 deaths. Health department officials attributed
the increase in cases to a stretch of wet weather followed by a short dry
spell recently.

