Date: Mon 23 Sep 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Austin American Statesman, Sun 22 Sep 2002
<http://www.austin360.com/statesman/editions/today/metro_state_9.html>

Texas: Dengue Fever Could Cross the Rio Grande from Tamaulipas
--------------------------------------------------------------
BROWNSVILLE: As the Texas Department of Health confirms seven of 24
suspected cases of dengue fever in Matamoros, Tamaulipas, [Mexico]
officials in Brownsville fear the mosquito-borne illness could easily make
its way across the Rio Grande to the city. "The majority of the cases were
detected in low-lying colonias in the outskirts of the city because some of
those areas have poor drainage, which attracts mosquitoes," said Ernesto
Chanes, Matamoros' public health director. So far, the disease has not
crossed into Brownsville, where officials said it has been three years
since a dengue case was reported. That case resulted in the death of one man.
The confirmed cases in Matamoros are [the classic form of] dengue fever,
and no deaths have been reported, Chanes told The Brownsville Herald in its
Friday editions. Brownsville's Public Health Director Josuecq Ramirez said
mosquitoes carrying dengue could easily bring it across the border. "The
risk is there. There are no barriers. The mosquitoes can easily migrate to
this side of the Rio Grande," Ramirez said. "There's no wall or screen that
would stop them."
A binational spraying effort is ongoing in response to the West Nile virus
outbreak. Officials expect it to intensify as dengue concerns increase. [On
the Mexican side of the border] officials continue to spray about 200
colonias where the dengue cases were detected. Matamoros has more than 400
colonias. Matamoros health Department officials reported 6 confirmed
classic dengue cases of 34 suspected cases in the city last year.
